Some planets outside the Solar System are known to have atmospheric clouds. In October 2013, the detection of high altitude optically thick clouds in the [[atmosphere]] of [[exoplanet]] [[Kepler-7b]] was announced,&lt;ref name=&quot;MIT-20131002&quot;&gt;{{cite web |last=Chu |first=Jennifer |title=Scientists generate first map of clouds on an exoplanet |url=http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2013/scientists-generate-first-map-of-clouds-on-kepler-7b-1003.html |date=2 October 2013 |website=[[MIT]] |access-date=2 January 2014 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1088/2041-8205/776/2/L25|arxiv=1309.7894| title = Inference of Inhomogeneous Clouds in an Exoplanet Atmosphere| journal = The Astrophysical Journal| volume = 776| issue = 2| pages = L25| year = 2013| last1 = Demory | first1 = B. O. | last2 = De Wit | first2 = J. | last3 = Lewis | first3 = N. | last4 = Fortney | first4 = J. | last5 = Zsom | first5 = A. | last6 = Seager | first6 = S. | last7 = Knutson | first7 = H. | last8 = Heng | first8 = K. | last9 = Madhusudhan | first9 = N. | last10 = Gillon | first10 = M. | last11 = Barclay | first11 = T. | last12 = Desert | first12 = J. M. | last13 = Parmentier | first13 = V. | last14 = Cowan | first14 = N. B. |bibcode=2013ApJ...776L..25D|s2cid=701011}}&lt;/ref&gt; and, in December 2013, in the atmospheres of [[GJ 436 b]] and [[GJ 1214 b]].&lt;ref name=&quot;NASA-20131231&quot;&gt;{{cite web |last1=Harrington |first1=J.D. |last2=Weaver |first2=Donna |last3=Villard |first3=Ray |title=Release 13-383 – NASA's Hubble Sees Cloudy Super-Worlds With Chance for More Clouds |url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2013/december/nasas-hubble-sees-cloudy-super-worlds-with-chance-for-more-clouds/ |date=31 December 2013 |website=[[NASA]] |access-date=1 January 2014 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;NAT-20140101a&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/505031a| title = Extrasolar planets: Cloudy with a chance of dustballs| journal = Nature| volume = 505| issue = 7481| pages = 31–32| year = 2014| last1 = Moses | first1 = J. |bibcode = 2014Natur.505...31M | pmid=24380949| s2cid = 4408861}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;NAT-20140101b&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nature12887| title = A featureless transmission spectrum for the Neptune-mass exoplanet GJ 436b| journal = Nature| volume = 505| issue = 7481| pages = 66–68| year = 2014| last1 = Knutson | first1 = H. A. | last2 = Benneke | first2 = B. R. | last3 = Deming | first3 = D. | last4 = Homeier | first4 = D. |arxiv = 1401.3350 |bibcode = 2014Natur.505...66K | pmid=24380953| s2cid = 4454617}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;NAT-20140101c&quot;&gt;{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nature12888| title = Clouds in the atmosphere of the super-Earth exoplanet GJ 1214b| journal = Nature| volume = 505| issue = 7481| pages = 69–72| year = 2014| last1 = Kreidberg | first1 = L. | last2 = Bean | first2 = J. L. | last3 = Désert | first3 = J. M. | last4 = Benneke | first4 = B. R. | last5 = Deming | first5 = D. | last6 = Stevenson | first6 = K. B. | last7 = Seager | first7 = S. | last8 = Berta-Thompson | first8 = Z. | last9 = Seifahrt | first9 = A. | last10 = Homeier | first10 = D. |arxiv = 1401.0022 |bibcode = 2014Natur.505...69K | pmid=24380954| s2cid = 4447642}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==In culture and religion==
[[File:Benjamin West - Joshua passing the River Jordan with the Ark of the Covenant - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|''[[Joshua Passing the River Jordan with the Ark of the Covenant]]'' (1800) by [[Benjamin West]], showing [[Yahweh]] leading the Israelites through the desert in the form of a [[Pillar of Cloud|pillar of cloud]], as described in {{Bibleverse||Exodus|13:21–22|9}}&lt;ref name=&quot;Gertz&quot;/&gt;]]
Clouds play an important role in various cultures and religious traditions. The ancient [[Akkadian Empire|Akkadians]] believed that the clouds were the breasts of the sky goddess [[Antu (goddess)|Antu]]&lt;ref name=&quot;Nemet-Nejat&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last=Nemet-Nejat|first=Karen Rhea|author-link=Karen Rhea Nemet-Nejat|date=1998|title=Daily Life in Ancient Mesopotamia|publisher=Greenwood|series=Daily Life|isbn=978-0313294976|page=[https://archive.org/details/dailylifeinancie00neme/page/182 182]|url=https://archive.org/details/dailylifeinancie00neme/page/182}}&lt;/ref&gt; and that rain was milk from her breasts.&lt;ref name=&quot;Nemet-Nejat&quot;/&gt; In {{Bibleverse||Exodus|13:21–22|9}}, [[Yahweh]] is described as guiding the [[Israelites]] through the desert in the form of a &quot;[[Pillar of Cloud|pillar of cloud]]&quot; by day and a &quot;[[Pillar of Fire (theophany)|pillar of fire]]&quot; by night.&lt;ref name=&quot;Gertz&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=Gertz|first1=Jan Christian|chapter=The Miracle at the Sea: Remarks on the Recent Discussion about Origin and Composition of the Exodus Narrative|title=The Book of Exodus: Composition, Reception, and Interpretation|date=2014|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden, The Netherlands|isbn=978-90-04-28266-7|page=111|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TmGeBQAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA111}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In the [[ancient Greek comedy]] ''[[The Clouds]]'', written by [[Aristophanes]] and first performed at the [[Dionysia|City Dionysia]] in 423 BC, the philosopher [[Socrates]] declares that the Clouds are the only true deities&lt;ref name=&quot;Strauss1966&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=Strauss|first1=Leo|title=Socrates and Aristophanes|date=1966|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago, Illinois|isbn=978-0-226-77719-1|pages=17–21, 29|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vce_OEKtTf4C}}&lt;/ref&gt; and tells the main character Strepsiades not to worship any deities other than the Clouds, but to pay homage to them alone.&lt;ref name=&quot;Strauss1966&quot;/&gt; In the play, the Clouds change shape to reveal the true nature of whoever is looking at them,&lt;ref name=&quot;Roche&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=Roche|first1=Paul|title=Aristophanes: The Complete Plays: A New Translation by Paul Roche|date=2005|publisher=New American Library|location=New York City, New York|isbn=978-0-451-21409-6|pages=149–150}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Strauss1966&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Robson&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=Robson|first1=James|title=Popular Culture in the Ancient World|date=2017|publisher=Cambridge University Press|editor-last=Grig|editor-first=Lucy|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=978-1-107-07489-7|page=81|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=isKSDQAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA81}}&lt;/ref&gt; turning into [[centaur]]s at the sight of a [[long hair|long-haired]] politician, wolves at the sight of the [[Embezzlement|embezzler]] Simon, deer at the sight of the coward [[Cleonymus of Athens|Cleonymus]], and mortal women at the sight of the effeminate [[Theoroi|informer]] [[Cleisthenes (son of Sibyrtius)|Cleisthenes]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Roche&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Robson&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Strauss1966&quot;/&gt; They are hailed the source of inspiration to comic poets and philosophers;&lt;ref name=&quot;Strauss1966&quot;/&gt; they are masters of [[rhetoric]], regarding [[eloquence]] and [[sophistry]] alike as their &quot;friends&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Strauss1966&quot;/&gt; 

In China, clouds are symbols of luck and happiness.&lt;ref name=&quot;Ding&quot;&gt;{{cite book|last1=Ding|first1=Ersu|title=Parallels, Interactions, and Illuminations: Traversing Chinese and Western Theories of the Sign|date=2010|publisher=University of Toronto Press|location=Toronto, Canada|isbn=978-1-4426-4048-1|page=118|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hLeQ8eDWNGUC&amp;pg=PT118}}&lt;/ref&gt; Overlapping clouds are thought to imply eternal happiness&lt;ref name=&quot;Ding&quot;/&gt; and clouds of different colors are said to indicate &quot;multiplied blessings&quot;.&lt;ref name=&quot;Ding&quot;/&gt;

Cloud watching or cloud gazing is a popular children's activity involving watching the clouds and looking for shapes in them, a form of [[pareidolia]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=How to start: Cloudgazing|url=https://discovertheforest.org/activities/cloudgazing}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Do You See Faces In The Clouds? The Science of Pareidolia|url=https://www.farmersalmanac.com/is-that-a-face-in-the-clouds-pareidolia-21911}}&lt;/ref&gt;

